{
  "texts": [
    "These models were predominantly encoder-only models which were made into classifiers by replacing the linear layer that predicts masked tokens with another randomly initiated linear layer (i.e.",
    "the classification head).Encoder transformer-based pretrained language models are typically given a classification head, where the loss function is cross-entropy 1 (e.g., see Rodrigues et al. 2019).",
    "Many previous authors have applied transformer-based language models to AES and ASAS in this way (Ormerod, 2022; Rodriguez et al., 2019; Sung et al., 2019; Uto & Uchida, 2020; Yang et al., 2020).",
    "Indeed, this is the current paradigm in most of AES and ASAS systems.While this paradigm (of affixing a classification head) could also be applied to GLMs,foot_3 this disregards the relationship learned by the model between the linear layer that predicts tokens and the transformer layers.",
    "The final output layer, however, can be left as is, and fine-tuning can focus on the intermediate layers (e.g., using QLoRA, described below)."
  ]
}